WEBVTT

00:06.220 --> 00:08.010
<i>Multiple protests</i>
<i>around the country</i>

00:08.210 --> 00:10.140
<i>as the Shared Data Act meets</i>
<i>resistance on Capitol Hill.</i>

00:10.340 --> 00:11.190
<i>HAYDEN: </i>
<i> You want to stop the Data Act?</i>

00:11.390 --> 00:13.060
<i>Then we need to show up.</i>

00:13.260 --> 00:14.280
<i>BEN:</i>
<i>We should kill that Kyle kid.</i>

00:14.480 --> 00:16.670
He could be working for Crowley.

00:16.870 --> 00:18.850
And he might just be
an innocent FBI informant.

00:19.050 --> 00:20.680
Who are you?!

00:20.880 --> 00:22.500
All the political donations
and PACs

00:22.700 --> 00:24.990
that Intaverse Media gives
money to are publicly available.

00:25.190 --> 00:27.600
I looked at
the executive level donations.

00:27.800 --> 00:30.770
They only ever contributed
to one politician

00:30.970 --> 00:35.120
on a regular basis-- Senator
Nora Evers of New Jersey.

00:36.730 --> 00:37.860
- Cover your ears!
- What?

00:41.120 --> 00:42.560
- [rapid gunfire]
- [groaning]

00:44.430 --> 00:45.700
What did I miss?

00:45.900 --> 00:47.920
You're missing
the most obvious version.

00:48.120 --> 00:50.270
- That Valence sold us out.
- Stop saying that!

00:50.470 --> 00:52.750
- He knew where all
the safe houses were.
- He didn't do it.

00:52.950 --> 00:55.400
- This was not the plan.
- Shut up!

00:57.010 --> 00:58.060
WEIR:
Miles, no!

00:58.260 --> 00:59.930
<i>It was you.</i>

01:00.130 --> 01:01.800
You were the last person
to talk to Valence.

01:02.000 --> 01:02.980
Why the fuck
didn't you tell me?

01:03.180 --> 01:04.420
If I told you that,

01:04.620 --> 01:06.030
I would have had
to tell you everything else.

01:06.230 --> 01:08.160
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>What else is there to tell?</i>

01:08.360 --> 01:10.070
<i>BEN:</i>
<i>Your team--</i>
<i>they're dead, all of 'em.</i>

01:13.370 --> 01:15.420
["El Santo Negro"
by Antonio Maravilla playing]

01:20.950 --> 01:22.390
<i>CROWLEY:</i>
<i>Truth is,</i>

01:22.590 --> 01:24.000
our democracy works no different

01:24.200 --> 01:25.790
than any of these shitholes
we traffic in.

01:25.980 --> 01:28.880
Are we really going to have
this conversation right now?

01:29.070 --> 01:31.660
Yeah! Look at this.
We've been grooming this guy

01:31.860 --> 01:34.530
- for months, Ben.
- I told them no heroin.

01:34.730 --> 01:36.100
But they don't listen.

01:36.300 --> 01:39.410
We find our sap to kill
El Comrade Generalissimo.

01:39.610 --> 01:42.930
We break him, program him,
rebuild him.

01:43.130 --> 01:44.930
- Hold on.
- Blood, sweat and tears.

01:45.130 --> 01:46.500
- It's hard, right?
- Yeah.

01:46.700 --> 01:48.370
Then the day before the hit,
this shit happens.

01:48.570 --> 01:50.030
BEN:
We'll figure
something else out.

01:50.230 --> 01:52.810
Yeah. I'm sorry, Langley.

01:53.010 --> 01:54.380
No president this year.

01:54.580 --> 01:56.120
What does any of this have to do
with democracy?

01:56.320 --> 01:59.430
Oh, stop it, will you? Please.
How many times...

01:59.630 --> 02:01.470
Araña talks the talk
we feed him,

02:01.670 --> 02:03.000
but how long
before he figures out

02:03.200 --> 02:04.650
how things really work
and then sells out?

02:04.850 --> 02:06.170
He'll control all the wealth
and resources

02:06.370 --> 02:07.780
this country has to offer.

02:07.980 --> 02:09.790
At the end of the day,
the only thing

02:09.990 --> 02:11.790
you need to ask yourself is,

02:11.990 --> 02:14.090
"Why are we giving control
to men like him

02:14.290 --> 02:17.360
when we could be selling it
to the highest bidder instead?"

02:17.560 --> 02:20.010
Or, hell,
taking it for ourselves.

02:20.210 --> 02:22.020
You're fucking crazy.

02:22.220 --> 02:23.450
[Crowley laughs]

02:23.650 --> 02:25.620
Time for change.

02:26.970 --> 02:29.010
[sighs]

02:30.970 --> 02:33.020
What about this one?

02:38.980 --> 02:41.120
♪

02:41.320 --> 02:43.290
<i>[indistinct, overlapping</i>
<i>news broadcasts]</i>

03:01.920 --> 03:05.480
[distorted, indistinct speech]

03:09.180 --> 03:11.280
Because safety has a price.

03:11.480 --> 03:13.720
Security takes a huge toll.

03:13.920 --> 03:17.240
And those who say they prize
privacy over all things,

03:17.440 --> 03:19.250
I have to ask--
what do you have to hide?

03:19.450 --> 03:21.160
[applause]

03:21.360 --> 03:22.900
<i> NEWSMAN: Evers' staunch support</i>
<i>of the Shared Data Act</i>

03:23.100 --> 03:25.510
<i>was thought to be a weakness</i>
<i>for her campaign,</i>

03:25.710 --> 03:27.600
<i>as the bill has struggled</i>
<i>its way through the Senate.</i>

03:27.800 --> 03:30.170
<i> The public is wary of the plan,</i>
<i>so the question now is</i>

03:30.370 --> 03:33.780
<i>if her inexplicable surge</i>
<i>in the race can continue.</i>

03:33.980 --> 03:35.610
<i>NEWSWOMAN: Once the clear</i>
<i>front-runner, the former</i>

03:35.810 --> 03:38.090
<i>vice president abruptly</i>
<i>abandoned his campaign today.</i>

03:38.290 --> 03:40.750
<i>NEWSMAN 2: A field full</i>
<i>of contenders has dwindled</i>

03:40.950 --> 03:43.620
<i> to just a few after yet another</i>
<i>candidate has dropped out</i>

03:43.820 --> 03:46.710
<i>for unspecified</i>
<i>personal reasons.</i>

03:46.910 --> 03:48.410
Are you tired of living in fear?

03:48.610 --> 03:50.410
The Data Act
isn't about privacy.

03:50.610 --> 03:52.190
It's about eliminating fear

03:52.390 --> 03:53.890
and making this the safest

03:54.090 --> 03:57.240
and most powerful democracy
in the world.

03:57.440 --> 03:59.240
[applause and cheering]

03:59.440 --> 04:04.060
[crowd chanting indistinctly]

04:09.980 --> 04:13.900
♪

04:34.880 --> 04:37.010
BEN:
Johnathan?

04:38.840 --> 04:40.880
Are you okay?

04:44.240 --> 04:45.380
I'm thinking maybe
I should just go ahead

04:45.580 --> 04:46.550
and do your part of this.

04:46.750 --> 04:49.340
No, no. We stick to the plan.

04:49.540 --> 04:52.240
No, you killed the plan.

04:53.770 --> 04:55.520
All right.

04:55.720 --> 04:57.520
I'm sorry.

04:57.720 --> 04:59.870
Okay?

05:00.070 --> 05:02.610
I'm sorry. I must have said it
a thousand times.

05:02.810 --> 05:05.390
No, actually, this is
the first time you've said it.

05:07.210 --> 05:11.220
Doesn't matter. I just
want to be done with this.

05:13.220 --> 05:15.270
And then what?

05:16.660 --> 05:18.700
Johnathan?

05:21.190 --> 05:24.320
It matters to me
what you think of me.

05:27.320 --> 05:30.930
You really must have been
something back in the day.

05:32.540 --> 05:35.240
Problem is I just
don't believe you anymore.

05:37.240 --> 05:39.330
<i>HAILEY [on comms]:</i>
<i>She's coming your way, Ben.</i>

05:44.950 --> 05:46.990
[indistinct chatter]

05:51.390 --> 05:54.270
BEN:
Oh, people, you have to move.

05:54.470 --> 05:56.620
Can't be here.
Please, please. All right.

05:56.820 --> 05:59.800
Um, this is her. The rest
of the motorcade got delayed.

06:00.000 --> 06:01.800
What the fuck? The senator's
already running late.

06:02.000 --> 06:03.450
They should have been here
ten minutes ago.

06:03.650 --> 06:04.930
- How's this even happening?
- Oh,

06:05.130 --> 06:06.630
well, you know,
a madwoman out front

06:06.830 --> 06:08.240
caused a bit of a traffic jam.

06:08.440 --> 06:12.110
- [horns honking]
- [indistinct shouting]

06:12.310 --> 06:14.070
But we're working
on getting your people here

06:14.270 --> 06:15.470
as fast as possible.

06:15.670 --> 06:17.890
- Oh...
- [Evers speaking indistinctly]

06:19.590 --> 06:21.520
What the fuck, Lanneman?
Is this Billy?

06:21.720 --> 06:23.520
Yes, ma'am. We're just waiting.

06:23.720 --> 06:25.520
Yeah, I'm not waiting.
You wait for the others.

06:25.720 --> 06:28.310
I'll see you all at 6:00.

06:28.500 --> 06:30.090
[siren wailing in distance]

06:30.290 --> 06:32.260
[engine starts]

06:35.480 --> 06:38.780
Billy, tell me
we have more wine.

06:39.790 --> 06:40.970
Who the fuck are you?

06:41.170 --> 06:43.090
I just want to talk.
Don't be afraid.

06:44.140 --> 06:46.790
Who said anything
about being afraid?

06:52.540 --> 06:54.070
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>The money loops</i>

06:54.270 --> 06:55.980
through every
anonymous financial entity

06:56.180 --> 06:57.860
on the planet.

06:58.060 --> 07:00.210
Someone has been illegally
feeding millions of dollars

07:00.410 --> 07:02.720
to you and your campaign,
and we can prove it.

07:06.460 --> 07:07.780
Come on, Senator.

07:07.980 --> 07:10.260
You want the White House,
go get it.

07:10.460 --> 07:13.250
All I want--
the man pulling the strings.

07:15.260 --> 07:17.440
- No.
- Excuse me?

07:17.640 --> 07:19.440
- [chuckles]
- This is enough
to take you down.

07:19.640 --> 07:21.310
Enough?

07:22.310 --> 07:24.620
Enough?

07:24.820 --> 07:27.630
What you have-- it'll dominate
one news cycle, sure.

07:27.820 --> 07:29.630
Hurt my chances? Maybe.

07:29.830 --> 07:32.060
I have to stay a senator
for a more few years,

07:32.260 --> 07:35.500
then try again? Boo-hoo.

07:35.700 --> 07:38.150
It's nothing compared
to what they have on me.

07:39.980 --> 07:41.900
One day, they send a car for me.

07:42.100 --> 07:45.430
I'm blindfolded,
taken to a location.

07:45.630 --> 07:49.430
I'm shown a safety deposit box
with a briefcase inside.

07:49.630 --> 07:52.610
It's a metal one,
right out of the movies.

07:52.810 --> 07:54.520
And inside are materials.

07:54.720 --> 07:57.790
Hugely compromising materials.

07:57.990 --> 08:00.750
Let's just say
that if that gets out,

08:00.940 --> 08:02.750
anyone who's got my last name--

08:02.950 --> 08:05.130
they're gonna change it
to something else.

08:08.130 --> 08:11.580
I hear his gravelly voice
in my sleep.

08:11.780 --> 08:14.500
And I regret ever
playing ball with him.

08:14.700 --> 08:17.360
But there's no way
I'm gonna help you.

08:19.360 --> 08:22.500
If we helped you get your case
back, would you help us?

08:24.540 --> 08:27.160
Yes, but it's not gonna happen.

08:27.360 --> 08:29.470
I was blindfolded.

08:29.670 --> 08:31.120
I know the number of the box.

08:31.320 --> 08:32.780
I have no idea
where the vault is.

08:32.980 --> 08:34.610
You said you were picked up
from where?

08:34.800 --> 08:36.820
- 3rd and D.
- Surface streets or highways?

08:37.020 --> 08:38.830
Do you think
you left the city?

08:39.030 --> 08:41.480
Surface. I assumed
that I was still in the city.

08:41.680 --> 08:43.050
I heard a food cart nearby.

08:43.250 --> 08:45.620
HOMM:
It was 1550 Girard.

08:45.820 --> 08:47.620
Let me guess, it smelled
like chicken and garlic

08:47.820 --> 08:49.970
and it was a Tuesday.

08:50.170 --> 08:53.060
1550 Girard is an ultra-secure

08:53.260 --> 08:55.800
private depository
used by shady rich people.

08:56.000 --> 08:59.720
Uh, cartels, tax cheats,
criminals, money launderers.

08:59.920 --> 09:01.720
It's kind of famous in my world.

09:01.920 --> 09:05.060
Arif's Shawarma is there
on Tuesdays.

09:07.020 --> 09:09.460
Well?

09:10.460 --> 09:12.820
Can you do it, Weir?

09:13.020 --> 09:15.250
You obviously have
a very talented team.

09:19.770 --> 09:23.260
Mr. Heston,
welcome to 1550 Girard.

09:23.460 --> 09:25.920
Ronald Kolgin.
So sorry to keep you waiting.

09:26.120 --> 09:27.920
Not a problem.

09:28.120 --> 09:29.830
And will you be joining
Mr. Heston

09:30.030 --> 09:32.580
on the tour of the facility
today, Mister...

09:32.780 --> 09:34.490
<i>BEN:</i>
<i>You agreed to a chaperone?</i>

09:34.690 --> 09:37.150
Store-brand G.I. Joe over there?

09:37.350 --> 09:39.540
- WEIR: It got handled.
- BEN: What were you thinking?

09:39.740 --> 09:41.540
- I should have been there.
- I told you, it got done.

09:41.740 --> 09:44.500
You didn't think I can
go on tour and take notes?

09:44.700 --> 09:46.290
- Didn't have a choice.
- There's always a choice.

09:46.480 --> 09:48.460
You don't get
to say that to me now.

09:48.660 --> 09:50.030
We handled it. Get over it.

09:50.230 --> 09:52.200
No one's talking to you.

09:52.400 --> 09:54.030
He's really gonna fuck us.
You realize that?

09:54.230 --> 09:56.160
LANNEMAN:
I could say the same thing
about you.

09:56.360 --> 09:58.080
Whatever's in that briefcase
is too valuable

09:58.280 --> 09:59.650
to trust to you criminals.

09:59.850 --> 10:01.560
It doesn't leave my sight.

10:01.760 --> 10:04.300
And you're gonna protect it like
you did your boss lady? Yes?

10:04.500 --> 10:05.960
Respect me, Grandpa.

10:06.160 --> 10:08.180
I'm the only one here
who knows the box number,

10:08.380 --> 10:09.870
so you don't have a choice.

10:10.070 --> 10:12.140
He is definitely gonna fuck us.

10:12.340 --> 10:14.180
WEIR:
No one is getting fucked.

10:14.380 --> 10:16.580
The senator's gonna get
what she wants,

10:16.780 --> 10:18.960
she's gonna give us Crowley,
and then it's done.

10:19.960 --> 10:22.060
What's he got on her?

10:22.260 --> 10:24.840
You can tell me. Pee-pee tapes?

10:26.970 --> 10:29.970
Oh. <i>ScheiBße</i>tapes.
Pew.

10:31.190 --> 10:32.510
So, what's my part?

10:32.710 --> 10:34.510
- Nothing.
- What?

10:34.710 --> 10:36.120
I don't want anyone
getting hurt.

10:36.320 --> 10:37.470
You're cutting me out?

10:37.670 --> 10:39.690
You and Homm are in the van.

10:39.890 --> 10:41.340
John, you can't do this
on your own.

10:41.540 --> 10:43.300
Well, I'd love to call my team
and get some help,

10:43.500 --> 10:44.690
but someone got them killed.

10:44.890 --> 10:46.860
You and Homm--
in the fucking van.

10:53.870 --> 10:57.360
Uh, that go for me, too?

10:57.560 --> 10:59.880
No. You're with me.

11:00.080 --> 11:01.880
<i>The client has to sign</i>
<i>into their system,</i>

11:02.080 --> 11:03.410
<i>enter their box number.</i>

11:03.610 --> 11:05.230
<i>Once they've been verified,</i>

11:05.430 --> 11:06.890
<i> they're given a specific route</i>
<i>to the vault.</i>

11:07.090 --> 11:08.630
<i>That's because</i>
<i>the entire place is covered</i>

11:08.830 --> 11:11.410
<i>in infrared motion sensors.</i>
<i>You get an escort.</i>

11:11.610 --> 11:13.500
<i>As long as you stick</i>
<i>to the prescribed route,</i>

11:13.700 --> 11:15.500
<i>none of the alarms</i>
<i>get activated.</i>

11:15.700 --> 11:16.940
<i>But if you don't...</i>

11:17.140 --> 11:18.330
- And our state-of-the-art...
- [alarm blaring]

11:18.530 --> 11:21.030
Sorry. My-my bad.

11:21.230 --> 11:23.770
<i>...the entire place goes</i>
<i>immediately into lockdown.</i>

11:23.970 --> 11:27.520
That's okay.
CP-1. Accidental trigger.

11:27.720 --> 11:29.080
Reset.

11:29.280 --> 11:30.080
- [chime]
- [alarm stops]

11:30.280 --> 11:32.650
Wow. Interesting system.

11:32.850 --> 11:34.690
The best.

11:36.560 --> 11:39.790
We have something for you
in the 800 section,

11:39.990 --> 11:41.840
as per your request.

11:42.040 --> 11:45.190
Thank you.
Eight's my lucky number.

11:45.390 --> 11:46.930
Now, by the time
you finally get to the vault,

11:47.130 --> 11:48.670
it's old school.

11:48.870 --> 11:50.410
<i> Takes two keys to open the door</i>
<i>to access the box.</i>

11:50.610 --> 11:52.020
<i>The clients and the escorts.</i>

11:52.220 --> 11:53.930
Three, two, one. Turn.

11:54.930 --> 11:57.940
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>To avoid diving</i>

11:58.140 --> 11:59.980
deep into the minutia,
the simple version:

12:00.180 --> 12:03.510
we walk in with an identical
case to the one in the vault,

12:03.710 --> 12:05.730
distract the escort,
switch the cases out,

12:05.930 --> 12:07.250
and walk out the front door.

12:07.450 --> 12:08.820
HAILEY:
[scoffs] Is that all?

12:09.020 --> 12:10.210
How-how are you gonna
get the keys?

12:10.410 --> 12:11.650
Well, I'll have
to pick one lock

12:11.850 --> 12:13.080
and then I'll use a copy
of the master key

12:13.280 --> 12:14.430
for the other one.

12:14.630 --> 12:15.700
A copy?
How are you gonna do that?

12:15.900 --> 12:17.220
Already did.

12:17.420 --> 12:19.000
You'll have your own key,

12:19.200 --> 12:21.880
and your escort will hold on

12:22.080 --> 12:23.440
to the master.

12:23.640 --> 12:24.970
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>It's actually not that hard.</i>

12:25.170 --> 12:27.490
Scale a photo, trace it
to a blank, cut the key.

12:27.690 --> 12:29.750
- Slick.
- But you still
haven't told me what...

12:29.950 --> 12:31.930
- what you want me to do.
- Well,

12:32.130 --> 12:33.500
given a large percentage

12:33.700 --> 12:35.540
of their clientele
is morally questionable,

12:35.740 --> 12:37.280
in order to use their facility,

12:37.480 --> 12:39.070
we have to make
a $20 million deposit

12:39.270 --> 12:41.970
in escrow
for the duration of our visit.

12:46.150 --> 12:48.160
Oh. No.

12:48.360 --> 12:50.160
- No. No!
- You'll get it right back.

12:50.360 --> 12:51.600
You think
you can just use my money?

12:51.800 --> 12:52.950
Hailey, it's not your money.

12:53.150 --> 12:54.690
It's absolutely my money.

12:54.890 --> 12:57.080
Oh, my God. Are you serious?
We're gonna be long gone

12:57.280 --> 12:59.090
before they even realize
that they've been robbed, okay?

12:59.290 --> 13:00.480
So as soon as I'm out, I promise

13:00.680 --> 13:01.920
I will give it
right back to you.

13:02.120 --> 13:03.660
<i>If</i>you get out.
What if it goes wrong?

13:03.860 --> 13:05.350
It's not gonna go wrong.

13:05.550 --> 13:07.010
I know how their system works,
and more importantly,

13:07.210 --> 13:09.740
I know how their people work.
It's gonna be fine.

13:11.090 --> 13:13.800
It's gonna be fine.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.440
Oh, fuck.

13:20.880 --> 13:23.420
<i>SHAW: I know I've talked</i>
<i>about Edward Homm before.</i>

13:23.610 --> 13:27.940
But to quote the Dude,
"New shit has come to light."

13:28.140 --> 13:30.290
Remember this guy--
the one wanted for killing Homm?

13:30.490 --> 13:32.160
- Mm-hmm.
- That's John Weir.

13:32.360 --> 13:34.640
Most wanted guy
on the eastern seaboard.

13:34.840 --> 13:36.650
Well, my deep state contact,
Zaius, hipped me

13:36.850 --> 13:38.870
to a news story about a shootout

13:39.070 --> 13:42.170
in Upstate New York at a motel
just a few days ago.

13:42.370 --> 13:44.350
Wasn't a ton of good video.
See?

13:44.550 --> 13:46.700
<i>But Zaius said</i>
<i>the government processed it</i>

13:46.900 --> 13:48.790
<i> and said it was this Weir guy.</i>

13:48.990 --> 13:51.570
<i>Now my boy Benzo here's </i>
<i> pretty good with the Photoshop.</i>

13:51.770 --> 13:53.620
<i>He did a little up-rezzing,</i>
<i>little sharpening.</i>

13:53.820 --> 13:54.620
<i>Look what he came up with.</i>

13:54.820 --> 13:56.060
<i>Check it.</i>

13:56.260 --> 13:58.760
<i>- SHAW: Same profile, right?</i>
<i>- Mm-hmm.</i>

13:58.950 --> 14:01.110
<i>SHAW:</i>
<i>Same hair? Convincing?</i>

14:01.300 --> 14:02.760
<i>Now look here.</i>

14:02.960 --> 14:04.060
<i>There's an old guy with him</i>
<i>and a lady,</i>

14:04.260 --> 14:06.070
<i>but who's this here?</i>

14:06.270 --> 14:08.590
<i>He could be Asian, right?</i>

14:08.790 --> 14:10.030
<i>- Word.</i>
<i>- Right?</i>

14:10.230 --> 14:12.510
<i>Is that Edward Homm?</i>

14:12.710 --> 14:14.210
<i>I don't know.</i>

14:14.400 --> 14:16.820
<i>But Zaius also said,</i>
<i>"Call the morgue."</i>

14:17.020 --> 14:18.600
<i>And guess what? It turns out</i>

14:18.800 --> 14:21.690
<i>Ed's so-called body</i>
<i>was accidentally cremated</i>

14:21.890 --> 14:23.650
<i>before</i>
<i>it could be DNA-tested.</i>

14:23.850 --> 14:25.830
<i>- [laughing]</i>
<i>- Are you shitting me? I mean,</i>

14:26.030 --> 14:28.830
<i>you think this shit's</i>
<i>some kind of a coincidence?</i>

14:29.030 --> 14:32.220
<i> So, look, here's what I think.</i>
<i>I think Ed is not dead.</i>

14:32.420 --> 14:35.700
<i>I think Ed stumbled</i>
<i>onto something really big,</i>

14:35.900 --> 14:37.710
<i> and had to go underground to...</i>

14:37.910 --> 14:39.840
This is not good, right?

14:40.040 --> 14:41.710
BEN:
What?

14:41.910 --> 14:45.020
I said this-this probably
isn't very good, right?

14:45.220 --> 14:47.760
Well, he's a lunatic.
Nobody listens to him.

14:47.960 --> 14:50.680
He's got 23,000 hits.

14:50.880 --> 14:52.420
[scoffs]

14:52.620 --> 14:53.980
How's your wound?

14:54.180 --> 14:57.500
Uh, it's gonna scar for sure.

14:58.980 --> 15:01.030
How's yours?

15:06.290 --> 15:08.780
Just part of the job, right?

15:08.980 --> 15:11.220
We're not blood brothers
or anything.

15:11.420 --> 15:13.260
[laughs]

15:13.460 --> 15:15.430
Okay.

15:17.170 --> 15:19.140
You think Shaw really has, uh,

15:19.340 --> 15:21.140
an informant in the government?

15:21.340 --> 15:23.450
Sure. Same guy
who shot the moon landing

15:23.650 --> 15:26.890
in that studio in Area 51.

15:27.090 --> 15:29.720
It doesn't matter.

15:29.910 --> 15:31.720
They think
we're in Upstate New York.

15:31.920 --> 15:33.240
Okay.

15:33.440 --> 15:34.980
[taps key]

15:35.180 --> 15:36.850
<i>SHAW: </i>
<i> I'm telling you Ed is not dead.</i>

15:37.050 --> 15:38.810
HOMM:
He's got 31,000 hits.

15:39.010 --> 15:40.510
<i>Ed is not dead.</i>

15:40.710 --> 15:43.030
<i>Yeah, he's also got </i>
<i> a pretty cool street food blog.</i>

15:43.230 --> 15:47.040
<i>Sick. Yeah. </i>
<i> Bet you didn't know that, huh?</i>

15:47.240 --> 15:49.260
Phones in the Faraday bags.

15:49.460 --> 15:51.910
They don't come out
until the job is over.

15:52.110 --> 15:54.650
NSA's not the only one
parsing metadata.

15:54.850 --> 15:58.140
I need you, I call you on that,
and you answer.

15:58.330 --> 16:00.920
One unauthorized ping
in the system,

16:01.120 --> 16:04.450
I send in The Janitor
and his bone saw.

16:04.650 --> 16:08.750
MAN:
Yes, sir. So, what's the job?

16:08.950 --> 16:11.630
You're going out of town.

16:11.830 --> 16:13.970
Open.

16:26.940 --> 16:28.630
Hey.

16:33.550 --> 16:35.740
I need you to load in
your crypto wallet info,

16:35.940 --> 16:37.390
make a transfer.

16:37.590 --> 16:39.560
[sighs]

16:43.560 --> 16:45.610
[chuckles softly]

16:47.000 --> 16:50.190
How's this for what-ifs?

16:50.390 --> 16:51.880
What if, uh,

16:52.080 --> 16:54.020
this whole thing--

16:54.220 --> 16:56.630
everything that has happened

16:56.830 --> 16:58.630
up until now--

16:58.830 --> 17:00.890
the bar,

17:01.090 --> 17:04.330
the hotel, the safe houses,

17:04.530 --> 17:07.600
Crowley, everything--

17:07.800 --> 17:11.380
what if all of it

17:11.580 --> 17:14.250
is engineered to...

17:14.450 --> 17:17.130
to get me to this very moment?

17:17.330 --> 17:21.780
All of it created
to make me give you

17:21.980 --> 17:23.950
all of my money?

17:25.340 --> 17:27.220
I mean...

17:27.420 --> 17:29.530
it's what you do, right?

17:29.730 --> 17:31.700
Yeah.

17:33.530 --> 17:35.570
[Hailey sighs]

17:37.440 --> 17:39.020
[short chuckle]

17:39.220 --> 17:41.500
- All I got is your word.
- Mm-hmm.

17:41.700 --> 17:43.680
[chuckles]

17:43.870 --> 17:46.930
Pretty ironic, huh?

17:49.410 --> 17:51.760
That's all I've got
to give right now.

18:07.860 --> 18:09.910
HAILEY:
Fuck it. I'll do it.

18:25.930 --> 18:27.970
Thank you.

18:33.720 --> 18:36.070
You should get some sleep.

18:37.070 --> 18:38.430
Yeah, I know.

18:38.630 --> 18:41.810
Just-just... close your eyes.

18:54.480 --> 18:56.960
Okay.

19:00.180 --> 19:02.180
[footsteps departing]

19:18.150 --> 19:20.210
You know, we got a few
thousand square feet here

19:20.410 --> 19:23.080
if you want
to find your own space.

19:23.280 --> 19:25.780
I told you
I'm not taking my eyes off you.

19:25.980 --> 19:27.780
I'm good right here.

19:27.980 --> 19:29.950
Awesome.

19:40.650 --> 19:42.480
♪

20:00.630 --> 20:02.760
You think he's trying
to reach Valence?

20:07.200 --> 20:08.860
Maybe he had
a back channel going.

20:09.060 --> 20:10.740
He hasn't slept
in a couple days,

20:10.930 --> 20:12.820
but emailing a dead friend

20:13.020 --> 20:15.440
is a level beyond exhaustion.

20:15.640 --> 20:17.790
No. He's-he's just
not thinking clearly.

20:17.990 --> 20:20.570
I mean, it happens sometimes.

20:20.770 --> 20:23.220
He calls it
"going down the hole."

20:25.040 --> 20:26.490
He needs help.

20:26.690 --> 20:29.580
- Psychological help?
- Eventually, yeah, but

20:29.780 --> 20:31.410
right now, I just...

20:31.610 --> 20:33.670
I just mean he needs me.

20:33.870 --> 20:36.110
I should be with him on this op.

20:36.310 --> 20:38.110
I'll keep an eye
on him tomorrow.

20:38.310 --> 20:42.030
You're going and I'm not? Huh.

20:42.230 --> 20:45.070
And he thinks I'm the one
who's gonna hurt somebody?

20:45.270 --> 20:47.730
And he's trying
to contact a dead man.

20:47.930 --> 20:50.510
Did he tell you the plan?

20:50.710 --> 20:52.650
Hmm?

20:52.850 --> 20:54.860
What is it?

20:57.340 --> 21:00.470
I'm worried about him,
too, you know.

21:01.860 --> 21:03.440
But if there's a problem
with this plan,

21:03.640 --> 21:06.050
you don't have the experience
to see it,

21:06.250 --> 21:08.050
much less Evers' body man.

21:08.250 --> 21:11.270
And he'll cross you,
both of you.

21:11.470 --> 21:13.750
This is what I do.

21:14.830 --> 21:16.360
I can help.

21:17.360 --> 21:18.720
[soft chuckle]

21:18.920 --> 21:21.330
I see what you're doing there.

21:21.530 --> 21:24.230
Using your reverse psychology
or whatever.

21:25.710 --> 21:27.330
Playing on my empathy.

21:27.530 --> 21:29.460
I am not playing.

21:30.460 --> 21:31.940
He's my son.

21:32.940 --> 21:34.240
Mm-hmm.

21:38.290 --> 21:40.380
Good night.

21:43.040 --> 21:45.790
<i>[cheering, applause]</i>

21:45.990 --> 21:47.610
The Shared Data Act is just

21:47.810 --> 21:50.880
another way they dehumanize us.

21:51.080 --> 21:52.970
- [cheering]
- We are like

21:53.170 --> 21:55.880
these flesh and blood puppets,

21:56.080 --> 21:58.670
and they've got their hands
up our asses

21:58.870 --> 22:00.190
and they're pulling the strings,

22:00.390 --> 22:03.630
while we work and we work

22:03.830 --> 22:05.720
and they kill the planet.

22:05.920 --> 22:07.850
We kill for them!

22:08.050 --> 22:09.940
And all the while,
it's their shit

22:10.140 --> 22:12.250
and blood-covered hands
pulling the strings.

22:12.450 --> 22:14.120
- [cheering]
- Yes!

22:14.320 --> 22:17.300
Then they pull it out, they
shake the blood in our face

22:17.500 --> 22:21.000
and leave us in a heap
on the floor.

22:21.200 --> 22:23.390
I'm not okay with that.

22:23.590 --> 22:25.300
Are you okay with that?

22:25.500 --> 22:28.050
- [crowd voicing dissent]
- So what do we say?

22:28.250 --> 22:30.440
Take back your life!
Take back your life!

22:30.640 --> 22:32.140
And now what do we do?

22:32.340 --> 22:35.530
- MAN: Kill your master!
- WOMAN: Kill your master!

22:35.730 --> 22:39.320
- [crowd chanting]: Kill your
master! Kill your master!
- HAYDEN: Yeah!

22:39.520 --> 22:41.100
Kill your master!

22:41.300 --> 22:45.010
Kill your master!
Kill your master!

22:46.060 --> 22:47.710
ELIZA:
Baby, are-are you
really going to?

22:48.800 --> 22:51.330
KYLE:
Of course I am.
Are you out now?

22:51.530 --> 22:53.550
- Just make up your mind.
- Oh, baby, come on.

22:53.750 --> 22:55.550
I mean, I just...

22:55.750 --> 22:57.380
Baby, I've never
done anything like this.

22:57.580 --> 22:58.820
Well, you can help me,
like you said,

22:59.020 --> 23:00.510
or you can get out of my way.

23:00.710 --> 23:03.210
Okay?

23:03.410 --> 23:06.650
Look, I need to do this for me.
Okay? I-I... I just...

23:06.850 --> 23:08.350
I can't live like this anymore,
you know.

23:08.550 --> 23:11.000
I just want my life back.

23:11.200 --> 23:13.050
I want to help you, baby.
Really, really...

23:13.250 --> 23:15.400
Baby, I do. I do, baby.

23:15.600 --> 23:16.920
[mumbles, gasps]

23:17.120 --> 23:20.230
Ky. Kyle. Kyle, stop.

23:20.430 --> 23:22.320
Stop. Just,
I want to help you, baby.

23:22.520 --> 23:24.710
Really, just...
Just, baby, just stay.

23:24.910 --> 23:26.890
Just stay. [gasps]

23:27.090 --> 23:30.590
You know,
just fucking forget it!

23:30.790 --> 23:32.840
Okay? I'll just do it myself.

23:33.890 --> 23:36.070
I shouldn't have even told you.

23:36.270 --> 23:38.940
- Just forget
you know anything about me.
- [crying]

23:39.140 --> 23:41.730
- Okay?
- No, no, wait, baby, just...

23:41.930 --> 23:44.120
Kyle. Kyle. Kyle!

23:44.320 --> 23:45.990
No, just wait, just...

23:46.190 --> 23:48.080
Okay, I'll help you!

23:48.280 --> 23:51.130
Just-just...
just don't leave me.

23:51.330 --> 23:54.260
Ky... Don't leave me.

23:54.460 --> 23:56.400
Don't leave me!

23:56.600 --> 23:58.400
- Hey.
- Kyle.

23:58.600 --> 24:02.480
- Kyle. Kyle.
- It's okay. It's all right.

24:08.700 --> 24:10.750
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>Today's the day.</i>

24:13.970 --> 24:15.500
<i> Lanneman and I will go in firs,</i>

24:15.700 --> 24:18.200
<i> take possession of our new box,</i>
<i>make a deposit.</i>

24:18.400 --> 24:20.680
<i>With $20 million in escrow,</i>
<i>we can sign in,</i>

24:20.880 --> 24:23.380
<i>at which point we will be</i>
<i>escorted to the vault.</i>

24:23.580 --> 24:25.770
<i>You'll come in after us, take</i>
<i>a tour as a potential client.</i>

24:25.970 --> 24:28.650
<i>By that time,</i>
<i>we should be in the vault.</i>

24:28.840 --> 24:30.820
<i>Lanneman will distract </i>
<i> the escort and make the switch.</i>

24:31.020 --> 24:34.000
- [whispering]: Which one?
- 844.

24:34.200 --> 24:35.480
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>None of which can be possible</i>

24:35.680 --> 24:37.740
<i>until the alarm system's</i>
<i>been defeated.</i>

24:37.940 --> 24:39.920
- [alarm blaring]
<i> -And that's gonna be your job.</i>

24:40.120 --> 24:41.920
Wait, what? I...

24:42.120 --> 24:43.570
I... How am I gonna do that?

24:43.770 --> 24:45.140
I don't know alarms, computers,
any of that.

24:45.340 --> 24:47.360
- You don't have to.
- I don't?

24:47.560 --> 24:49.010
The weakest element
to any system

24:49.210 --> 24:51.020
is always gonna be
the human element.

24:51.210 --> 24:52.500
All you need is this.

24:52.690 --> 24:53.840
A pen?

24:54.040 --> 24:55.370
An infrared laser pointer.

24:55.570 --> 24:57.750
- Oh.
- Invisible to the naked eye.

24:59.670 --> 25:02.510
Oh... my God.

25:02.700 --> 25:03.640
<i>KOLGIN:</i>
<i>So sorry to keep you waiting.</i>

25:03.840 --> 25:05.600
<i>Are you ready for your tour?</i>

25:05.790 --> 25:07.380
<i>1550 Girard is the country's</i>

25:07.580 --> 25:09.600
preeminent
private sequestering facility.

25:09.800 --> 25:13.080
We pride ourselves
on both our discretion

25:13.280 --> 25:14.910
and our
state-of-the-art security.

25:15.110 --> 25:17.770
- [beep, alarm blaring]
- [gasps]

25:19.600 --> 25:23.220
- What is this?
<i>- LANNEMAN: W-Why</i>

25:23.420 --> 25:26.700
- is the door closing?
- It's okay. It's okay.

25:26.900 --> 25:28.310
He suffers from PTSD.

25:28.510 --> 25:30.790
- Claustrophobic.
- Jesus.

25:30.990 --> 25:32.270
You'll be all right.

25:32.470 --> 25:34.410
CP-7. Sensor error. Reset.

25:34.610 --> 25:37.320
- [chime, alarm stops]
- I'm so sorry.

25:37.520 --> 25:40.410
That has only happened
once before...

25:40.610 --> 25:42.670
[beep, alarm blaring]

25:44.630 --> 25:47.070
CP-7. Sensor error. Reset.

25:47.270 --> 25:49.330
Oh, Jesus.
Open the door.

25:49.530 --> 25:50.770
Can we ask them if they could
open the doors as quickly

25:50.970 --> 25:52.420
as possible, please?

25:52.620 --> 25:54.080
- [chime, alarm stops]
- Great.

25:54.280 --> 25:56.560
My deepest apologies, ma'am.
I can assure you that

25:56.760 --> 25:57.560
- that has never...
- [chime, alarm blaring]

25:57.760 --> 25:59.340
Oh, come on.

26:00.340 --> 26:02.220
I-I... I should probably

26:02.420 --> 26:04.130
take my valuables
to Eatonhurst like I...

26:04.330 --> 26:06.570
Oh, one moment.
Uh, if you could literally

26:06.770 --> 26:08.310
bear with us for one minute,

26:08.510 --> 26:10.960
we'll reboot the system
and everything will be fine.

26:11.160 --> 26:13.840
Kolgin. F Protocol.
Hard reboot the system.

26:14.040 --> 26:16.800
<i>Authorization GMRC-781.</i>

26:17.000 --> 26:18.930
- LANNEMAN: Open the door.
<i>- Kolgin. Repeat,</i>

26:19.130 --> 26:20.710
<i>- hard reboot.</i>
- [stammers] Open the doors!

26:20.910 --> 26:23.060
- Sir, you can't do that.
- Oh, the hell I can't.

26:23.260 --> 26:25.400
- Open the doors.
<i>- GUARD: Initiating.</i>

26:28.630 --> 26:30.640
All doors will remain shut

26:30.840 --> 26:32.770
until all sensors
and cameras are back online.

26:32.970 --> 26:34.810
It'll be less than
a minute, sir. Please.

26:35.010 --> 26:36.510
I was locked in a box in Iraq,

26:36.710 --> 26:37.950
and I'll be goddamned
they do it to me again!

26:38.150 --> 26:39.430
No one is gonna lock you up.

26:39.630 --> 26:40.910
We don't want
the smoke alarms triggered

26:41.110 --> 26:41.820
- as well, sir...
- You're not gonna lock me up!

26:42.020 --> 26:42.990
Open the doors!

26:44.690 --> 26:45.910
<i>They killed</i>

26:46.110 --> 26:47.700
everyone else in my unit.

26:47.900 --> 26:50.470
Shot 'em in the head.
They killed my whole team!

26:55.650 --> 26:57.490
Open the doors!

26:57.690 --> 26:59.320
GUARD:
18 seconds.

26:59.520 --> 27:00.580
15 seconds.

27:00.780 --> 27:01.970
- It'll just be 15 seconds.
- I...

27:02.170 --> 27:03.580
I heard, thank you.

27:03.780 --> 27:05.800
- Open the door!
- Take it easy!

27:06.000 --> 27:07.240
- Take it easy?
<i>- Nine.</i>

27:07.440 --> 27:08.940
- You don't understand.
<i>- Seven,</i>

27:09.140 --> 27:11.330
- I almost died in that box!
<i>- six, five,</i>

27:11.530 --> 27:14.200
- They killed everyone else
in my unit.
<i>- four, three.</i>

27:14.400 --> 27:16.160
<i>- Two, one.</i>
- HARLAND: Sir, please,
take it easy.

27:16.360 --> 27:18.380
- [beep]
<i>- GUARD: Back online.</i>
<i>All systems nominal.</i>

27:18.580 --> 27:21.980
I'm very sorry.
We should just lock up.

27:25.420 --> 27:27.600
[whispers]: I'm never seen him
react like that.

27:29.030 --> 27:31.300
Three, two, one.

27:33.040 --> 27:35.130
Uh, apologies.

27:47.010 --> 27:48.760
All better now.
It won't happen again.

27:48.960 --> 27:50.930
- Does this happen often?
- No.

27:51.130 --> 27:55.020
But better the alarms are overly
sensitive than not enough.

27:56.670 --> 27:58.900
- Should we see the vault?
<i>- WEIR [on comms]: Hailey,</i>
<i>we got to go.</i>

27:59.100 --> 28:01.250
- Wait. What?
<i>- I fucked up.</i>

28:01.450 --> 28:03.160
I left a key in Crowley's box.
We've got to get out of here

28:03.360 --> 28:05.860
<i>before they discover it.</i>

28:06.060 --> 28:09.300
Miss Wolcott.
The vault?

28:09.500 --> 28:11.650
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>Hailey, we got to go.</i>

28:11.850 --> 28:13.030
Let's get you checked out.

28:16.520 --> 28:18.960
<i>KOLGIN: </i>
<i> Miss Wolcott, should we go see</i>

28:19.160 --> 28:21.130
the vault?

28:25.790 --> 28:28.090
Okay. Let's see this vault.

28:29.050 --> 28:31.670
Is there a problem?

28:31.870 --> 28:33.490
One second.

28:35.100 --> 28:37.330
You will receive your,
uh, own key,

28:37.530 --> 28:39.810
and your escort will

28:40.010 --> 28:42.060
hold on to the master.

28:43.020 --> 28:45.680
Walking through
the opening protocol.

28:45.880 --> 28:47.770
You, uh, can choose a box

28:47.970 --> 28:49.860
or one will be chosen for you.

28:50.060 --> 28:52.300
- [alarming blaring]
- Sorry. Sorry. Sorry.
- For fuck sakes.

28:52.500 --> 28:54.690
Sorry.

28:54.890 --> 28:56.770
[Kolgin sighs]

29:01.910 --> 29:04.220
CP-7 sensor error. Reset.

29:04.420 --> 29:08.310
- Reset. Reset!
<i>- GUARD: Resetting.</i>

29:09.090 --> 29:11.360
[beep, alarm stops]

29:11.560 --> 29:14.280
[sighs]
I'm sorry, ma'am.

29:14.480 --> 29:17.980
I didn't mean to curse, but you
really need to be more careful.

29:18.180 --> 29:20.750
Your, uh, pen.

29:33.900 --> 29:35.940
<i>[on comms]: I've got it.</i>

29:47.260 --> 29:48.750
Well?

29:48.950 --> 29:50.440
Like clockwork. [panting]

29:50.640 --> 29:52.660
- Where's Weir?
- Right behind me.

29:52.860 --> 29:55.410
Thank you for your patience.
You're good to go, Mr. Heston.

29:55.610 --> 29:57.450
Thank you.

29:57.650 --> 29:58.800
<i>LANNEMAN:</i>
<i>Hell of a performance.</i>

29:59.000 --> 30:00.190
Well done.

30:00.390 --> 30:02.200
Thank you.

30:02.400 --> 30:04.370
By the way, do you know Pete?

30:04.570 --> 30:06.850
Who's Pete?

30:07.050 --> 30:09.070
<i>LANNEMAN:</i>
<i>That's Pete.</i>
<i>Give him the briefcase.</i>

30:09.270 --> 30:10.940
<i>HAILEY:</i>
<i>Oh, shit.</i>

30:11.140 --> 30:12.600
Fuck. I knew it.

30:12.800 --> 30:15.380
BEN:
I knew it. I knew it.

30:15.580 --> 30:16.860
I told you this was
going to happen.

30:17.060 --> 30:19.340
- Calm down. It's fine.
- You okay?

30:19.540 --> 30:20.940
Yeah.

30:24.860 --> 30:27.600
The briefcase you walked in with
was a decoy, right?

30:28.650 --> 30:30.350
You gave Lanneman the decoy,

30:30.550 --> 30:33.040
you put the real one
back in your box.

30:34.180 --> 30:37.180
Guess I should go back in
and get it.

30:45.710 --> 30:47.810
Hey.

30:48.010 --> 30:50.230
Thought you might want
to look in on your money.

30:52.190 --> 30:53.940
You got to hand it to me, Weir.

30:54.140 --> 30:55.550
That was black-belt level,

30:55.750 --> 30:58.900
110% trust on my part.

30:59.940 --> 31:02.520
Pretty fucking impressive,
if you ask me.

31:02.720 --> 31:05.220
Yes, it was. And thank you.

31:05.410 --> 31:07.040
You saved my ass back there.

31:07.240 --> 31:09.210
'Cause I screwed up, and...

31:10.210 --> 31:12.350
I wouldn't be standing here
if it wasn't for you.

31:12.550 --> 31:14.350
And I put you in a position
you should never have been in,

31:14.550 --> 31:15.920
and if something
had happened to you,

31:16.120 --> 31:18.480
I would never have
forgiven myself. So, I'm...

31:19.480 --> 31:21.620
I-I'm sorry.
Honestly, I...

31:21.820 --> 31:23.410
I don't know what happened.

31:23.610 --> 31:27.110
You showed that
you're an actual human being,

31:27.310 --> 31:28.660
capable of fucking up.

31:30.230 --> 31:32.890
And asking for help.

31:33.890 --> 31:35.890
And apologizing.

31:36.980 --> 31:39.110
Hmm.

31:43.240 --> 31:44.810
- What?
- [soft chuckle]

31:49.250 --> 31:51.340
I want to kiss you.

31:54.690 --> 31:57.050
[laughs softly]

31:57.250 --> 31:58.490
[laughs]

31:58.690 --> 32:00.650
Yeah.

32:01.650 --> 32:03.700
A friend once told me...

32:05.480 --> 32:07.700
...everybody's a sucker
for confidence.

32:14.580 --> 32:15.970
<i>[line ringing]</i>

32:20.150 --> 32:22.070
<i>WEIR:</i>
<i>Senator?</i>

32:22.270 --> 32:24.020
Oh, you're fucking good, Weir.

32:25.810 --> 32:27.780
I guess you own me now.

32:27.980 --> 32:30.340
- What is it I can do for you?
<i>- Same rules as before.</i>

32:30.540 --> 32:32.780
You give us everything we need

32:32.980 --> 32:34.780
to find our guy,
you get your case back.

32:34.980 --> 32:37.170
Meet at 3:00 p.m. sharp.
I'll text you the address.

32:38.650 --> 32:40.610
Damn, I'd love
to see her face right now.

32:40.810 --> 32:43.090
- [laughs]
<i>- [line ringing]</i>

32:45.130 --> 32:47.060
<i>- KYLE: Yes, sir.</i>
- Are you in position?

32:47.260 --> 32:48.800
<i>- Almost.</i>
- Well, hurry up.

32:49.000 --> 32:50.750
Every second matters
in this game.

33:11.290 --> 33:14.420
The master dies today.

33:17.080 --> 33:19.990
Bring the car around.

33:21.040 --> 33:22.960
You ready?

33:23.160 --> 33:25.820
Ready, baby.

33:34.920 --> 33:36.970
[indistinct chatter]

33:40.970 --> 33:42.850
[speaking indistinctly]

33:43.050 --> 33:45.020
♪

33:49.110 --> 33:50.550
[phone rings]

33:50.750 --> 33:53.850
John? John, phone.

33:55.850 --> 33:57.420
Thanks.

33:58.420 --> 34:00.910
Senator.

34:01.110 --> 34:03.740
- We're gonna be
a little bit late.
- [cheering]

34:03.940 --> 34:05.310
Why? I said 3:00 p.m. sharp.

34:05.510 --> 34:07.260
<i>My people--</i>
<i>they added a stump speech.</i>

34:14.920 --> 34:17.670
- That is not a good idea.
<i>- Oh,</i>

34:17.870 --> 34:19.020
don't be dramatic.

34:19.220 --> 34:20.400
- I'll be there.
- [gunshot]

34:22.450 --> 34:24.710
- [people screaming, shouting]
- LANNEMAN: Senator!

34:26.970 --> 34:28.070
Senator!

34:28.270 --> 34:29.500
Senator?

34:32.280 --> 34:33.330
[gun clatters]

34:35.290 --> 34:37.430
Senator? Goddamn it!

34:37.630 --> 34:38.780
Got him in my sights.

34:38.980 --> 34:40.650
Do it.

34:40.850 --> 34:41.990
The fuck just happened?

34:48.170 --> 34:49.130
[gunshot]

34:51.130 --> 34:53.130
♪

35:18.630 --> 35:20.990
<i>NEWSWOMAN:</i>
<i>MPD has recovered a gun</i>

35:21.190 --> 35:23.080
<i>and the shooter</i>
<i>remains at large.</i>

35:23.280 --> 35:25.340
<i>Now, we've received footage</i>
<i>from the scene.</i>

35:25.540 --> 35:28.160
<i>View discretion</i>
<i>is strongly advised.</i>

35:29.690 --> 35:31.390
<i>- [gunshot]</i>
<i>- [screaming, clamoring]</i>

35:31.590 --> 35:33.350
- Oh, my God.
<i>- In related news,</i>

35:33.550 --> 35:35.220
<i>the Senate majority leader</i>
<i>has called</i>

35:35.420 --> 35:37.050
<i>for an immediate vote</i>
<i>on the Shared Data Act.</i>

35:37.250 --> 35:40.190
<i> The bill Senator Evers herself</i>
<i>was championing.</i>

35:40.390 --> 35:42.230
<i>The once troubled legislation</i>
<i>will be brought</i>

35:42.430 --> 35:44.320
<i>to the floor</i>
<i>as soon as possible,</i>

35:44.520 --> 35:47.320
<i>and the polls are showing</i>
<i>strong bipartisan support.</i>

35:47.520 --> 35:48.450
Goddamn it!

35:48.650 --> 35:50.460
- Crowley.
- BEN: Yeah.

35:50.660 --> 35:52.500
Why would Crowley
kill his own candidate?

35:52.700 --> 35:54.500
'Cause this wasn't
about winning the presidency.

35:54.700 --> 35:56.380
This was about passing
a piece of legislation

35:56.580 --> 35:58.860
that the senator campaigned on.

35:59.060 --> 36:01.030
All he had to do was
have her assassinated.

36:01.230 --> 36:02.690
Reshape the narrative.

36:02.890 --> 36:04.990
Bright young senator
cut down in her prime

36:05.190 --> 36:07.300
by the radicals she promised
to protect us from.

36:07.500 --> 36:09.350
Turn her into a martyr,
guaranteeing

36:09.540 --> 36:12.300
that her legislation would pass.

36:12.500 --> 36:14.390
When that happens,

36:14.590 --> 36:16.610
Crowley gains access
to thousands of data points

36:16.810 --> 36:19.750
on every single American
with a cell phone

36:19.950 --> 36:21.870
or a computer.

36:22.870 --> 36:24.260
He can control anyone.

36:25.480 --> 36:27.320
Anything.

36:27.520 --> 36:29.490
♪

36:50.550 --> 36:52.300
- You did so great, baby.
- Mwah.

36:52.500 --> 36:54.300
- Thank you so much.
- [chuckles]

36:54.500 --> 36:55.830
I love you.

36:56.030 --> 36:57.440
I do. I love you.

36:57.640 --> 36:59.050
You know, you're perfect.

36:59.250 --> 37:01.130
Like, I knew it
from the day we met.

37:02.910 --> 37:04.960
Well... [chuckles]

37:06.090 --> 37:09.060
Just took so long to find you.

37:09.260 --> 37:10.620
[European accent]: You know
how many girls' Facebooks

37:10.820 --> 37:13.100
we had to scrape
in order to find someone?

37:13.300 --> 37:16.150
[giggles] What's wrong
with your voice, baby?

37:16.350 --> 37:18.200
You know, with the right mix?
Passion for politics,

37:18.400 --> 37:20.020
- Hey.
- angry.

37:20.220 --> 37:21.770
You know, so lonely.

37:21.960 --> 37:24.150
Struggles with mental illness.

37:25.150 --> 37:26.470
No attachment disorders.

37:26.670 --> 37:29.340
- Wait, Kyle...
- Most importantly, someone

37:29.540 --> 37:31.470
I could stand to fuck.

37:31.670 --> 37:33.390
- Kyle...
- With enough data, you can make

37:33.590 --> 37:35.870
people do whatever
you want them to.

37:36.070 --> 37:37.780
It's funny,
you haven't been on your meds

37:37.980 --> 37:39.650
- for almost six months now.
- [whimpering]

37:39.850 --> 37:41.830
'Cause I started
changing them out.

37:42.030 --> 37:44.310
And then, little by little,

37:44.510 --> 37:46.530
now you're
basically homeopathic.

37:46.730 --> 37:48.440
And like he said, you know,

37:48.640 --> 37:51.840
"Make her... make her need you,"
he said.

37:52.040 --> 37:53.880
[grunting]

37:54.080 --> 37:56.750
You know,
"Like she needs oxygen."

38:00.840 --> 38:03.020
And then I started
hitting the dog

38:03.220 --> 38:04.980
and I started petting the dog.

38:05.180 --> 38:07.990
Like, "Oh, I love you," or
then I kind of, like, hate you,

38:08.180 --> 38:09.720
you know...

38:10.850 --> 38:13.820
"I'm leaving, I'm staying."

38:14.020 --> 38:15.650
He said...

38:15.840 --> 38:17.820
"When you hand her the gun,

38:18.020 --> 38:20.680
<i>"She'll take it</i>
<i>because she wants to.</i>

38:21.510 --> 38:23.770
And because she loves you."

38:26.080 --> 38:28.130
You know?

38:32.000 --> 38:34.050
[exhales]

38:35.050 --> 38:38.020
You know, "And then we'll make
sure she gets away clean,

38:38.210 --> 38:41.240
'cause we don't
want to get caught."

38:41.440 --> 38:43.150
You know? And then

38:43.350 --> 38:45.330
spilling the beans.

38:45.530 --> 38:47.490
[chuckles]

38:51.930 --> 38:54.770
You know, "spilling the beans,"
that's...

38:54.970 --> 38:56.900
that's another one.

38:57.100 --> 38:58.910
[chuckles]

38:59.110 --> 39:01.300
L-O-L.

39:01.500 --> 39:03.900
- Okay.
- [engine starts]

39:04.950 --> 39:07.130
<i>NEWSMAN:</i>
<i>We just received word</i>

39:07.330 --> 39:09.700
<i>Senator Evers, after being</i>
<i>in critical condition,</i>

39:09.900 --> 39:12.400
<i> has passed away this afternoon.</i>

39:12.600 --> 39:14.310
Fucking bastard.

39:14.510 --> 39:16.140
<i>Preliminary reports</i>
<i>have identified the shooter</i>

39:16.340 --> 39:18.530
<i> as Eliza Wells of New York Cit.</i>

39:18.730 --> 39:21.100
<i>Her social media presence </i>
<i> shows a person deeply entrenchd</i>

39:21.300 --> 39:23.890
<i>in fringe political causes.</i>

39:24.090 --> 39:26.590
<i>And in at least one post,</i>
<i>she mentions her struggles</i>

39:26.790 --> 39:28.810
<i>with depression</i>
<i>and bipolar disorder.</i>

39:29.000 --> 39:30.940
Straight out
of the patsy playbook.

39:31.140 --> 39:33.200
<i> MPD are still searching for her</i>

39:33.400 --> 39:35.510
<i>and are asking if anyone</i>
<i>has any information</i>

39:35.710 --> 39:38.080
<i>to please contact them</i>
<i>immediately.</i>

39:38.270 --> 39:39.560
<i>Eliza Wells was</i>
<i>last seen on foot,</i>

39:39.750 --> 39:42.820
<i>running from the park</i>
<i>moments after...</i>

39:43.020 --> 39:45.070
♪

39:59.480 --> 40:01.520
[newswoman speaking
indistinctly]

40:05.270 --> 40:07.310
♪

